    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.1-2_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">1</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Box 719
                        Great Bend, Kans.
                        Jan. 7, 1942
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am making arrangements for the sending of a book--or books-- to my mother and Dad in China by the first person to go over there. The book that  I want is John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardts "The Song of Jed Smith," especially recommended to me by a friend of mine in <unclear/>, Hazel Bennett Baker. Dad, when he visited us in 1939 enroute back to China thought so much of your writing that he gave each in his family a copy of "The Song of the Messiah" I <hi rend="underline">believe</hi> he'd heard you speak at Atlantic City, <hi rend="caps">N.J.</hi> I wonder 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.20.1-2_0002"/>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                    <fw type="authorial">II</fw>
                    
                    if I'm right--.</p>
                
                <p>The very great favor I am going to ask of you is this: would you be so <hi rend="underline">kind</hi> as to autograph to Mother and Dad a copy of "The Song of Jed Smith" and send it to me <hi rend="caps">C.O.D.</hi> This will make a grand gift the perfect gift. I have left after that <figure><figDesc>An arrow pointing to "Smith"</figDesc></figure> <del/> $3.50 which I <hi rend="double underline">hope</hi> will buy the rest of your "Cycle of the West" -- he has the "Song of the Messiah" If the $3.50 will not purchase the remainder of the books I leave the choice of books to your judgement. And of course, send them all <hi rend="caps">C.O.D.</hi></p>
                
                <p>You know, I have hopes that someday I will have the honor of meeting you since your home is quite close to "our place in the Ozarks" which is a mile out of <unclear>Noel</unclear>.</p>
                
                A very successful year to you,
                and-Hopefully yours
                    <signed>Margaret Graham Trimmell
                    (Mrs. John A.)</signed>
                </opener>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
